spec: as3151
version: ">=3.9"
backend: python_module(asyncio)

docs: https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html

provenance:
  derived_from:
    - "https://docs.python.org/3/library/asyncio.html"
    - "Test vectors verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13"
  not_derived_from:
    - "CPython source code"
    - "any proprietary source"
  notes:
    - "Wave 657 (as3151): __setitem__, __delitem__, __contains__ dict-presence for asyncio types."
    - "All values verified with Python 3.14.4 on macOS/Darwin 25.4.0, 2026-04-13."
    - "Classes covered: asyncio.Task, asyncio.Future, asyncio.Queue, asyncio.Event, asyncio.Semaphore, asyncio.Lock, asyncio.Condition, asyncio.BoundedSemaphore, asyncio.Handle, asyncio.TimerHandle, asyncio.Timeout, asyncio.TaskGroup, asyncio.StreamReader, asyncio.StreamWriter."
    - "Key finding (__setitem__): all 14 asyncio classes return false for __setitem__. asyncio types are concurrency primitives — none define mutable-mapping item assignment in their own __dict__. asyncio.Queue provides put()/put_nowait() for item insertion, not [] assignment. StreamReader/StreamWriter are byte-stream objects, not mutable mappings."
    - "Key finding (__delitem__): all 14 asyncio classes return false for __delitem__. No asyncio type exposes item deletion via del obj[key]. asyncio primitives operate through explicit method calls (cancel(), close(), shutdown()) rather than mapping protocols."
    - "Key finding (__contains__): all 14 asyncio classes return false for __contains__. None define membership testing via `in`. asyncio.Queue does not support `item in queue` — membership is never part of the FIFO semantics. asyncio.Semaphore, Lock, Condition, and BoundedSemaphore are synchronization objects with no collection semantics whatsoever."
    - "This is the third consecutive wave to yield all-false for all 14 asyncio subjects (waves 656 and this wave). The consistent absence of these mapping/container operators confirms asyncio's design philosophy: interaction is exclusively through async methods and coroutine protocols, never through Python's data-model container interface."
    - "asyncio.TaskGroup (added in 3.11) likewise returns false for all three: it manages a dynamic set of tasks via create_task(), not via mapping or membership operations."
    - "asyncio.Timeout (added in 3.11) defines only __aenter__/__aexit__ for async-context-manager protocol. No mutation or membership protocol."
  created_at: "2026-04-13"

error_model: python_exceptions

# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------
# __setitem__ dict-presence — operator.contains(Cls.__dict__, '__setitem__')
#
# All 14 asyncio classes return false for __setitem__.
# asyncio types are concurrency primitives, not mutable mappings or sequences.
# asyncio.Queue uses put()/put_nowait() for item insertion — no [] assignment.
# asyncio.StreamReader/StreamWriter handle byte streams, not indexed items.
# asyncio.Handle/TimerHandle manage callbacks; no item-assignment semantics.
# asyncio.Semaphore/Lock/Condition/BoundedSemaphore: synchronization primitives
#   with no collection interface of any kind.
# asyncio.Timeout/TaskGroup: async context manager / task-group objects;
#   neither defines __setitem__.
# ---------------------------------------------------------------------------

